Land Acquisition Priority is given to acquire lands or rights needed to protect or aid in the recovery of this species (Forest Plan, p. 94).
Examples where the Forest has acquired lands for this purpose include: Â· Â· Â· Acquisition of stream corridors that now, or in the future, may serve as Indiana bat habitat.
Acquisition of lands in 1993 (US Tract 956) adjacent to a known Indiana bat hibernaculum that represent "key areas" of Indiana bat habitat for this site.
Acquisition of lands in 1985 (US Tract 1403a) that contain nearly all of the Cave Hollow Arbogast System, a known Indiana bat hibernacula and "Critical Habitat" for VA big-eared bat.
Closing bat caves to public use and periodic monitoring by biologists, law enforcement, and other FS personnel has reduced or eliminated human visitation in MNF caves during the time they are occupied, which is beneficial to this bat.
