SHALE BARREN ROCK CRESS Arabis serotina Threatened
Nine shale barren rock crest sites are known on the MNF.
No shale barren rock crest has been found since the 1989 endangered listing.
Potential and known habitat within the entire MNF is estimated to be less than 100 acres.
No designated critical habitat for shale barren rock crest exists on the MNF.
Consultation and Cooperation Â· Consistent with Forest Plan standard 1560 (M) (1), management and implementation of this species' Recovery Plan is coordinated with WVDNR, universities, Forest Service research, USFWS, The Nature Conservancy, etc.
One example is the cooperation and participation between the MNF and WVDNR in a Conservation Assessment of the MNF's shale barrens communities.
Habitat Protection and Improvement and Protection of Individuals Mid-Appalachian shale barrens generally are characterized by open (
Open herbaceous cover adapted to this harsh environment also can occur (USFWS, 1991a).
Often the slope is undercut by a stream directly below the shale barren.
Shale barrens are south- to southwest-facing, narrowly endemic sites on shale ridge balds.
They exist on Devonian-age shales of the Brallier formation between 1300-2500 ft (396-762 m) elevations (Keener, 1983).
Protection of Occupied Habitat Â· Known populations, including an appropriate buffer around each population, are avoided.
Protection or Development of Suitable Habitat Â· Potential project areas are surveyed for this species' habitat and adverse effects are avoided.
Â· Shale barrens and an appropriate buffer around each barren are protected via Forest-wide and Appendix K standards D1(c) (16) and D2b (7) (Forest Plan, p. 87 and Appendix K-15 and K-17).
Â· Most Forest authorized activities (other than activities such as research/information gathering) are prohibited within shale barrens (Forest Plan, p. 87).
Â· Road construction/reconstruction near shale barren areas is limited.
Â· No active management is implemented at this time for this species.
If inventory results indicate that populations are declining and need some type of active management, then the USFWS, WVDNR, and current research would be consulted on appropriate measures to take.
Monitoring/Inventory/Survey Â· Consistent with Forest Plan standard 2670 (h), surveys for shale barren rock cress are conducted prior to conducting any activity on National Forest System land within Greenbrier County, WV.
Such surveys have provided additional information on this species.
About 1000 acres have been surveyed for shale barrens using specific geology and aerial photos.
